  "prompt": "What is a principal root? How is it used in Mathematics?",
  "response": "In mathematics, the term \"principal root\" refers to the primary root of a number or expression, typically the non-negative root in the context of real numbers. When dealing with square roots, the principal square root of a non-negative number \\( x \\) is the non-negative number \\( y \\) such that \\( y^2 = x \\). This is often denoted as \\( \\sqrt{x} \\).\n\nFor example, the principal square root of 9 is 3, because 3 is the non-negative solution to \\( y^2 = 9 \\).\n\nThe concept of principal root is most commonly applied to square roots, but it can extend to other types of roots. For instance, the principal cube root of a number \\( x \\) is the real number \\( y \\) such that \\( y^3 = x \\).\n\nIn complex numbers, the principal root is typically the root with the smallest non-negative argument (angle) in the polar or exponential form of the complex number.\n\nPrincipal roots are used in various mathematical contexts, including solving equations, calculus, and complex number theory. They help to define functions and ensure consistency when dealing with multiple possible solutions. For example, when defining the square root function on the set of non-negative real numbers, the principal square root ensures that the function is well-defined and single-valued.",
